data.content:
Here's how to structure your tests using modern MSTest patterns:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class DataFetcherTests
{
    private readonly TestContext _testContext;

    public DataFetcherTests(TestContext testContext)
    {
        _testContext = testContext;
    }

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(5000)]
    public async Task FetchAsync_ValidUrl_ReturnsContent()
    {
        // Arrange
        var handler = new FakeHttpMessageHandler("hello world", HttpStatusCode.OK);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

        // Act
        var result = await fetcher.FetchAsync(
            "https://example.com", _testContext.CancellationToken);

        // Assert
        Assert.AreEqual("hello world", result);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(5000)]
    public async Task FetchAsync_ServerError_ThrowsHttpRequestException()
    {
        // Arrange
        var handler = new FakeHttpMessageHandler("", HttpStatusCode.InternalServerError);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

        // Act & Assert
        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            async () => await fetcher.FetchAsync(
                "https://example.com", _testContext.CancellationToken));
    }

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(2000)]
    public async Task FetchAsync_CancellationRequested_ThrowsOperationCanceled()
    {
        // Arrange
        var handler = new NeverCompletesHandler();
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        cts.Cancel(); // pre-cancel

        // Act & Assert
        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<TaskCanceledException>(
            async () => await fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com", cts.Token));
    }

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(3000)]
    public async Task FetchAsync_SlowResponse_RespectsCancellation()
    {
        // Arrange
        var handler = new DelayedHandler(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(100));

        // Act & Assert — token fires after 100ms, well before the 10s delay
        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<TaskCanceledException>(
            async () => await fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com", cts.Token));
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| Pattern | Why |
|---|---|
| `[Timeout(N)]` + `_testContext.CancellationToken` | Cooperative timeout — MSTest cancels the token when the timeout expires, preventing hung tests |
| `Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<T>` | Verifies the exact exception type with a clear failure message (not `[ExpectedException]`) |
| Separate `CancellationTokenSource` for cancellation tests | Lets you control cancellation independently from MSTest's timeout |
| `sealed` test class | Performance and design best practice |

**Fake handlers** you'd need:

```csharp
// Returns a canned response
file sealed class FakeHttpMessageHandler(string content, HttpStatusCode status)
    : HttpMessageHandler
{
    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        return Task.FromResult(new HttpResponseMessage(status)
        {
            Content = new StringContent(content),
        });
    }
}

// Never completes — useful for cancellation tests
file sealed class NeverCompletesHandler : HttpMessageHandler
{
    protected override async Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        await Task.Delay(Timeout.Infinite, cancellationToken);
        throw new InvalidOperationException("Should never reach here");
    }
}

// Completes after a delay — useful for timeout race tests
file sealed class DelayedHandler(TimeSpan delay) : HttpMessageHandler
{
    protected override async Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        await Task.Delay(delay, cancellationToken);
        return new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.OK);
    }
}
```

The critical pattern: **always flow `TestContext.CancellationToken`** into your async calls when using `[Timeout]`. Without it, `[Timeout]` can't cooperatively cancel the test — it would have to abort the thread, which is unreliable.
